s","identityProvidersList.numberOfIdentityProviders":"{number} providers","util.noResources":"No resources to display","util.noMatches":"No matches","util.match":"match","util.matches":"matches","util.pagePreference":"Preferences","util.confirm":"Confirm","util.save_preferences":"Save preferences","util.cancel":"Cancel","util.apply":"Apply","util.wrapLines":"Wrap lines","util.pageSize":"Page size","util.wrapLinesDescription":"Select to see all the text and wrap the lines","util.visibleCols":"Select visible columns","util.change":"Change","util.rows":"{number} rows","util.filtering.placeholder":"Filter results by text, property or value","util.filtering.value":"Value","util.filtering.group.values":"Values","util.filtering.property":"Property","util.filtering.group.properties":"Properties","util.filtering.operation.and":"and","util.filtering.operation.or":"or","util.filtering.operator":"Operator","util.filtering.operators":"Operators","util.filtering.operators.lessThan":"Less than","util.filtering.operators.lessThanOrEqual":"Less than or equal","util.filtering.operators.greaterThan":"Greater than","util.filtering.operators.greaterThanOrEqual":"Greater than or equal","util.filtering.operators.contains":"Contains","util.filtering.operators.doesNotContain":"Does not contain","util.filtering.operators.equals":"Equals","util.filtering.operators.doesNotEqual":"Does not equal","util.filtering.edit":"Edit filter","util.filtering.allProperties":"All properties","util.filtering.showMore":"Show more","util.filtering.showLess":"Show less","util.filtering.clear":"Clear filters","util.aria.filtering":"your choice","util.aria.dismiss":"Dismiss message","util.aria.nextPage":"Next page","util.aria.previousPage":"Previous page","util.aria.pageLabel":"Page {number} of all pages","util.aria.success":"Success","util.aria.error":"Error","util.aria.inProgress":"In progress","providers.create.type.saml.description":"Establish trust between your AWS account and a SAML 2.0 compatible Identity Provider such as Shibboleth or Active Directory Federation Services.","providers.create.type.openId.description":"Establish trust between your AWS account and Identity Provider services, such as Google or Salesforce.","providers.create.form.header":"Add an Identity provider","providers.create.configure.header":"Configure provider","providers.create.type.label":"Provider type","providers.create.formActions.button.cancel":"Cancel","providers.create.formActions.button.addProvider":"Add provider","providers.create.notification.saml.success.message":"{idpName} added. You must assign an IAM role to start using this provider.","providers.create.notification.openId.success.message":"{idpName} added. You must assign an IAM role to start using this provider.","providers.create.notification.originalOpenId.success.message":"Identity provider added. You must assign an IAM role to start using this provider.","providers.create.notification.provider.error.message":"Identity provider was not added.","providers.create.notification.provider.loading.message":"Creating identity provider.","providers.create.notification.button.viewProvider":"View provider","providers.create.notification.button.assignRole":"Assign role","providers.create.openId.providerUrl.label":"Provider URL","providers.create.openId.providerUrl.description":"Specify the secure OpenID Connect URL for authentication requests.","providers.create.openId.providerUrl.hintText":'Maximum 255 characters. URL must begin with "https"',"providers.create.openId.providerUrl.errorText.validate.message":"Valid characters required.","providers.create.openId.providerUrl.errorText.duplicate.message":"A provider with this URL already exists.","providers.create.openId.providerUrl.errorText.required.message":"Provider URL is required.","providers.create.openId.providerUrl.errorText.maxLength.message":"Count exceeds 255 characters limit.","providers.create.openId.providerUrl.button.getThumbprint":"Get thumbprint","providers.create.openId.providerUrl.button.editUrl":"Edit URL","providers.create.openId.thumbprint.errorText.required.message":"Get the thumbprint before adding this provider.","providers.create.openId.verifyThumbprint.alert.header":"Verify thumbprint","providers.create.openId.verifyThumbprint.section.header.label":"Use the following thumbprint to verify the certificate of the provider.","providers.create.openId.verifyThumbprint.section.header.description":"Users authenticated by this provider can access your AWS account as long as the providers' certificate does not change. When the provider's certificate changes, you must provide the thumbprint of the new certificate.","providers.create.openId.verifyThumbprint.section.content.thumbprint.label":"Thumbprint","providers.create.openId.verifyThumbprint.section.content.issuedBy.label":"Issued by","providers.create.openId.verifyThumbprint.section.content.caValidity.label":"CA validity","providers.create.openId.verifyThumbprint.section.content.caValidity.value":"From {fromDate} to {toDate}","providers.create.openId.audience.label":"Audience","providers.create.openId.audience.description":"Specify the client ID issued by the Identity provider for your app.","providers.create.openId.audience.hintText":"Maximum 255 characters. Use alphanumeric or ':_.-/' characters.","providers.create.openId.audience.errorText.validate.message":"Valid characters required.","providers.create.openId.audience.errorText.required.message":"Audience is required.","providers.create.openId.audience.errorText.maxLength.message":"Count exceeds 255 characters limit.","providers.create.saml.providerName.label":"Provider name","providers.create.saml.providerName.description":"Enter a meaningful name to identify this provider","providers.create.saml.providerName.hintText":"Maximum 128 characters. Use alphanumeric or '._-' characters.","providers.create.saml.providerName.errorText.validate.message":"Valid characters required.","providers.create.saml.providerName.errorText.duplicate.message":"A provider with this name already exists.","providers.create.saml.providerName.errorText.required.message":"Provider name is required.","providers.create.saml.providerName.errorText.maxLength.message":"Count exceeds 128 characters limit.","providers.create.saml.metadataDocument.label":"Metadata document","providers.create.saml.metadataDocument.description":"This document is issued by your IdP.","providers.create.saml.metadataDocument.hintText":"File needs to be a valid UTF-8 XML document.","providers.create.saml.metadataDocument.errorText.validation.required":"Metadata document is required.","providers.create.saml.metadataDocument.buttonText":"Choose file","idp.saml.details.help.learnMoreText":"Learn more","idp.saml.details.help.staticLinkText":"SAML 2.0-based Federation","idp.saml.details.help.additionalResourcesText":"Additional resource","idp.saml.details.help.pageHeader":"IAM Identity Providers","idp.saml.details.help.pageBody":"<p>IAM identity providers (IdPs) manage user identities outside of AWS. You can establish a trust relationship with an IdP to give external user identities permissions to use AWS resources in your account. That way, you don’t have to create and manage IAM users yourself. IdPs do these tasks for you</p><p>Using an IdP might be useful if your organization already has its own identity system, such as a corporate user directory. Also, if you are creating a mobile app or web application that requires access to AWS resources, using an IdP can help keep your AWS account secure. You don’t have to distribute or embed long-term security credentials, such as access keys, in your applications.</p><p>To use an IdP, create an IAM identity provider entity to establish a trust relationship between your AWS account and the IdP. IAM supports IdPs that are compatible with <openid>OpenID Connect (OIDC)</openid> or <samlLink>SAML 2.0 (Security Assertion Markup Language 2.0)</samlLink>.</p>","idp.saml.details.help.linkText":"Identity Providers and Federation","idp.saml.metadata.help.learnMoreText":"Learn more","idp.saml.metadata.help.staticLinkText":"SAML 2.0-based Federation","idp.saml.metadata.help.additionalResourcesText":"Additional resource","idp.saml.metadata.help.pageHeader":"IAM Identity Providers","idp.saml.metadata.help.pageBody":"<p>IAM identity providers (IdPs) manage user identities outside of AWS. You can establish a trust relationship with an IdP to give external user identities permissions to use AWS resources in your account. That way, you don’t have to create and manage IAM users yourself. IdPs do these tasks for you. </p><p>Using an IdP might be useful if your organization already has its own identity system, such as a corporate user directory. Also, if you are creating a mobile app or web application that requires access to AWS resources, using an IdP can help keep your AWS account secure. You don’t have to distribute or embed long-term security credentials, such as access keys, in your applications.</p><p>To use an IdP, create an IAM identity provider entity to establish a trust relationship between your AWS account and the IdP. IAM supports IdPs that are compatible with <openid>OpenID Connect (OIDC)</openid> or <samlLink>SAML 2.0 (Security Assertion Markup Language 2.0)</samlLink>.</p>","idp.saml.metadata.help.linkText":"Identity Providers and Federation","idp.oidc.details.help.learnMoreText":"Learn more","idp.oidc.details.help.staticLinkText":"SAML 2.0-based Federation","idp.oidc.details.help.additionalResourcesText":"Additional resource","idp.oidc.details.help.pageHeader":"IAM Identity Providers","idp.oidc.details.help.pageBody":"<p>IAM identity providers (IdPs) manage user identities outside of AWS. You can establish a trust relationship with an IdP to give external user identities permissions to use AWS resources in your account. That way, you don’t have to create and manage IAM users yourself. IdPs do these tasks for you</p><p>Using an IdP might be useful if your organization already has its own identity system, such as a corporate user directory. Also, if you are creating a mobile app or web application that requires access to AWS resources, using an IdP can help keep your AWS account secure. You don’t have to distribute or embed long-term security credentials, such as access keys, in your applications.</p><p>To use an IdP, create an IAM identity provider entity to establish a trust relationship between your AWS account and the IdP. IAM supports IdPs that are compatible with <openid>OpenID Connect (OIDC)</openid> or <samlLink>SAML 2.0 (Security Assertion Markup Language 2.0)</samlLink>.</p>","idp.oidc.details.help.linkText":"Identity Providers and Federation","idp.list.help.learnMoreText":"Learn more","idp.list.help.pageHeader":"IAM Identity Providers","idp.list.help.pageBody":"<p>IAM identity providers (IdPs) manage user identities outside of AWS. You can establish a trust relationship with an IdP to give external user identities permissions to use AWS resources in your account. That way, you don’t have to create and manage IAM users yourself. IdPs do these tasks for you. </p><p>Using an IdP might be useful if your organization already has its own identity system, such as a corporate user directory. Also, if you are creating a mobile app or web application that requires access to AWS resources, using an IdP can help keep your AWS account secure. You don’t have to distribute or embed long-term security credentials, such as access keys, in your applications.</p><p>To use an IdP, create an IAM identity provider entity to establish a trust relationship between your AWS account and the IdP. IAM supports IdPs that are compatible with <openid>OpenID Connect (OIDC)</openid> or <samlLink>SAML 2.0 (Security Assertion Markup Language 2.0)</samlLink>.</p>","idp.list.help.linkText":"Identity Providers and Federation","idp.create.help.learnMoreText":"Learn more","idp.create.help.staticLinkText":"SAML 2.0-based Federation","idp.create.help.additionalResourc