 of users to delete in the text input field.","user.add.policies.errorDetails.header":"Errors attaching policies to the user.","user.add.policies.errorDetails.template":"Policy {name} not added.","user.details.removePermissions.error.detail.policy.template":"Failed to remove {name} from user.","user.details.removePermissions.error.detail.group.template":"Failed to remove user from {name}.","user.details.addPermissions.error.detail.policy.template":"Failed to add {name} to user.","user.details.addPermissions.error.detail.group.template":"Failed to add user to {name}.","user.details.mfa.resync.authenticationCodeError":'"Authentication code must be {limit} digits."',"role.deletion.failed":"Deletion failed.","role.deletion.inProgress":"Deletion in progress.","role.trustEntities.andmore":"and {num} more.","organization.addUsersWizard.selectUsers.header":"Select users and groups","organization.addUsersWizard.selectUsers.description":"Select one or more users and groups that you want to give multi-account access to.","organization.addUsersWizard.selectPermissionSets.header":"Select permission sets","organization.addUsersWizard.selectPermissionSets.description":"Permission sets define the level of access that users and groups have to an AWS account. You can assign more than one permission set to a user. To ensure least privilege access to AWS accounts, users with multiple permission sets on an AWS account must pick a specific permission set when accessing the account and then return to the AWS access portal to pick a different set when necessary.","organization.addUsersWizard.permissionSets.header":"Permission sets","organization.addUsersWizard.review.header":"Review and submit","organization.addUsersWizard.review.submit":"Submit","organization.addUsersWizard.review.userGroups.title":"Step 1: Select users and groups","organization.addUsersWizard.review.userGroups.subtitle":"Users and groups","organization.addUsersWizard.review.userGroups.columns.name.header":"Username / Group name","organization.addUsersWizard.review.userGroups.columns.type.header":"Type","organization.addUsersWizard.review.userGroups.columns.type.user":"User","organization.addUsersWizard.review.userGroups.columns.type.group":"User group","organization.addUsersWizard.review.userGroups.loading":"Loading users and groups","organization.addUsersWizard.review.permissionSets.title":"Step 2: Select permission sets","organization.addUsersWizard.review.permissionSets.subtitle":"Permission sets","organization.addUsersWizard.review.permissionSets.loading":"Loading permission sets","organization.addUsersWizard.selectedPermissionSets.loading":"Loading permission sets","organization.entity.type.root":"Root","organization.entity.type.ou":"Organizational Unit (OU)","organization.entity.type.account":"Account","organization.entity.type.unknown":"Unknown","permissionSets.tableOptions.columns.name.propertyLabel":"Name","permissionSets.tableOptions.columns.name.groupValuesLabel":"Name values","permissionSets.tableOptions.columns.description.propertyLabel":"Description","permissionSets.tableOptions.columns.description.groupValuesLabel":"Description values","permissionSets.tableOptions.columns.arn.propertyLabel":"ARN","permissionSets.tableOptions.columns.arn.groupValuesLabel":"ARN values","permissionSets.tableOptions.pageSizeOptions.label":"{number} permission sets","permissionSets.tableOptions.contentSelector.name.label":"Permission set","permissionSets.tableOptions.contentSelector.description.label":"Description","permissionSets.tableOptions.contentSelector.arn.label":"ARN","permissionSets.columns.name.header":"Permission set","permissionSets.columns.description.header":"Description","permissionSets.columns.arn.header":"ARN","permissionSets.ampTable.description":"AWS managed policies are standalone policies that are created and managed by AWS. Different types of AWS managed policies enable you to grant predefined permissions for many common use cases. For example, you can use job function policies to grant permissions for common job functions, full access policies to grant service administrators full access to an AWS service, and partial access policies to grant specific levels of access to AWS services. You can select up to 10 managed policies.","dashboard.title":"IAM dashboard","dashboard.additionalInfo":"Additional information","dashboard.iamDoc":"IAM documentation","dashboard.iamVideo":"Videos, IAM release history and additional resources","dashboard.securityBestPractise":"Security best practices in IAM","dashboard.relatedService":"Related services","dashboard.awsOrg":"AWS Organizations","dashboard.SSO":"AWS IAM Identity Center","dashboard.SSO.instances":"Instances","dashboard.awsOrg.description":"Centrally create and manage all your AWS accounts.","dashboard.SSO.description":"Centrally manage federated access to multiple AWS accounts and business applications.","dashboard.tools":"Tools","dashboard.quickLink":"Quick Links","dashboard.myAccessKey":"My access keys","dashboard.WIF":"Web identity federation playground","dashboard.WIF.description":"Authenticate yourself to any of the supported web identity providers,see the requests and responses, obtain a set of temporary security credentials,and make calls to the Amazon S3 API using the credentials:","dashboard.policy_sim":"Policy simulator","dashboard.policy_sim.description":"The simulator evaluates the policies that you choose and determines the effective permissions for each of the actions that you specify.","dashboard.accountId":"Account ID","dashboard.accountAlias":"Account alias","dashboard.signInUrl.description":"Sign-in URL for IAM users in this account","dashboard.signInUrl":"Sign-in URL","dashboard.alias.Required":"Alias is required.","dashboard.alias.Exists":"The alias you want to use already exists.","dashboard.alias.Length":"The length of alias should be between 3 and 63.","dashboard.alias.validCharactersRequired":"Valid characters required.","dashboard.createAlias.header":"Customize alias for IAM users in this account.","dashboard.createAlias.description":"Input your preferred alias for this account. ","dashboard.createAlias.hintText":"The alias must be not more than 63 characters. Valid characters are a-z, 0-9, and - (hyphen).","dashboard.createAlias":"Create Alias","dashboard.editAlias":"Edit Alias","dashboard.create":"Create","dashboard.edit":"Edit","dashboard.deleteAlias.header":"Delete account Alias","dashboard.deleteAlias.description":"IAM users in this account will not be able to sign-in through the URL with this alias. They can still sign-in using the URL with the AWS account ID.","dashboard.securityAlert":"Security alerts","dashboard.securityAlert.description":"Alerts on important security vulnerabilities","dashboard.securityAlert.MFA.header":"Enable MFA for root user","dashboard.securityAlert.MFA.description":"Enable Multi-factor authentication (MFA) for the root user to improve security for this account.","dashboard.securityAlert.AccessKey.header":"Disable access keys for root user","dashboard.securityAlert.AccessKey.description":"We recommend you delete the access keys for root user and instead use access keys attached to an IAM user to improve security.","dashboard.securityAlert.AccessKey.button":"Disable Access Key","dashboard.account":"AWS account","dashboard.customer.managed.policies":"Customer managed policies","dashboard.resourceInsights":"Resource insights","dashboard.resourceInsights.description":"Insights on IAM resources to help you eliminate security risks in this account.","dashboard.resourceInsights.failure":"Fail to load resource.","dashboard.resourceInsights.limit.approching":"You are approaching your limit of available IAM resources.","dashboard.resourceInsights.limit.approched":"You have reached your limit of available IAM resources.","dashboard.resourceInsights.resource.limited":"Limit reached","dashboard.resourceInsights.resource.available":"{number} available","dashboard.sidenavigation.cloudtrail.popover.title":"Monitor IAM Identity Center","dashboard.sidenavigation.cloudtrail.recommended":"Recommended","dashboard.sidenavigation.cloudtrail.popover.body":"AWS CloudTrail is an AWS service that helps you enable operational and risk auditing, governance, and compliance of your AWS account. Use this service to monitor activity in IAM Identity Center. <a>Learn more about CloudTrail</a>","user.list.help.pageHeader":"Users","user.list.help.pageBody":"<p>If you have employees that require access to AWS, don't share root user credentials with them. Instead, create individual IAM users within your account that correspond to users in your organization. IAM users are not separate accounts; they are users within the same account. Each user can have its own unique set of long-term credentials for access to the AWS Management Console. You can also create an individual access key for each user so that the user can make programmatic requests to work with resources in your account. You can grant different permissions to each IAM user.</p><p>Alternatively, you can <sso>use AWS IAM Identity Center for authentication</sso>.</p>","user.list.help.linkText":"IAM Users","role.list.help.pageHeader":"Roles","role.list.help.pageBody":"<p>A role is an IAM identity that you can create in your account that has specific permissions. An IAM role has some similarities to an IAM user. Roles and users are both AWS identities with permissions policies that determine what the identity can and cannot do in AWS. However, instead of being uniquely associated with one person, a role can be assumed by anyone who needs it. A role does not have standard long-term credentials such as a password or access keys associated with it. Instead, when you assume a role, it provides you with temporary security credentials for your role session.</p><p>You can use roles to delegate access to users, applications, or services that don't normally have access to your AWS resources.</p>","role.list.help.linkText":"IAM roles","role.rolesAnywhere.help.pageHeader":"IAM Roles Anywhere","role.rolesAnywhere.help.pageBody":"<p>You can use IAM Roles Anywhere to authenticate your non AWS workloads with X.509 certificates. When workloads authenticate with IAM Roles Anywhere they can use the temporary security credentials provided by a role to access your AWS resources.</p>","role.rolesAnywhere.help.linkText":"Provide access for non AWS workloads","policy.list.help.pageHeader":"Policies","policy.list.help.pageBody":"<p>Policies are JSON documents in AWS that let you specify who has access to AWS resources, and what actions they can perform on those resources. You can attach a policy to an identity or resource to define their permissions. AWS evaluates these policies when the IAM principal (user or role) makes a request. Permissions in the policies determine whether the request is allowed or denied.</p>","policy.list.help.linkText":"Policies and permissions in IAM","policy.details.policyVersionsList.policyVersion":"Policy Version","policy.details.policyVersionsList.tableHeading":"Versions of this policy","policy.details.policyVersionsList.tableDescription":"Each time you update a policy, you create a new version. You can have up to 5 versions of a customer managed policy.","policy.details.policyVersionsList.setAsDefault":"Set as default","policy.details.policyVersionsList.default":"Default","policy.details.policyVersionsList.version":"Version","policy.details.tabs.permissions":"Permissions","policy.details.tabs.entitiesAttached":"Entities attached","policy.details.tabs.tags":"Tags","policy.details.tabs.versions":"Versions","policy.details.tagsList.tableDescription":"Tags are key-value pairs that you can add to AWS resources to help identify, organize, or search for resources.","policy.details.tagsList.key":"Key","policy.details.tagsList.value":"Value","policy.details.manageTags":"Tags for {name}","policy.details.entitiesList.entityName":"Entity name","policy.details.entitiesList.entityType":"Entity type","policy.details.permissionEntitiesList.tableHeading":"Attached as a permissions policy","policy.details.permissionEntitiesList.tableDescription":"You can attach this policy to entities to make these permissions effective for them.","policy.details.boundaryEntitiesList.tableHeading":"Attached as a permissions boundary","policy.details.boundaryEntitiesList.tableDescription":"Use this policy as a permissions boundary to control the maximum permissions that an entity can have. This is an advanced feature used to delegate permissions management to others.","policy.details.boundaryEntitiesList.actions.setBoundary":"Set boundary","policy.details.attachList.tableHeading":"Entities you can attach this policy to","policy.details.attachList.tableDescription":"Entities are IAM users, groups, roles and permissions sets","policy.details.attachList.attachPolicy":"Attach policy","policy.details.detachList.detachPolicy":"Detach policy","policy.details.attachPolicyToEntitySuccess":"Policy attached to {name}","policy.details.attachPolicyLoading":"Attaching policy...","policy.details.attachPolicyError":"Some entities are not attached.","policy.details.attachPoliciesToEntitiesSuccess":"Policy attached to {number} entities.","policy.details.detachPolicyFromEntitySuccess":"Policy detached from {name}.","policy.details.detachPolicyLoading":"Detaching policy...","policy.details.detachPolicyError":"Policy not detached.","policy.details.detachPoliciesFromEntitiesSuccess":"Policy detached from {number} entities.","policy.details.setPermissionsBoundary":"Set permissions boundary","policy.details.setPermissionsBoundary.error.header":"Error setting policy as permissions boundary.","policy.details.setPermissionsBoundary.error.template":"Boundary not set for entity {name}.","policy.details.setDefaultPolicyVersion.errorDetails.header":"Error setting default policy.","policy.details.setDefaultPolicyVersion.errorDetails.template":"Policy version {name} not set as default.","policy.details.attachPolicyFromEntitySuccess":"Policy attached to entity {name}.","policy.details.attachPoliciesFromEntitiesSuccess":"Policy attached to {number} entities.","policy.details.entities":"{number} entities","policy.details.attachPolicy.errorDetails.header":"Errors attaching policy to entities.","policy.details.attachPolicy.errorDetails.template":"Policy not attached to {name}.","policy.details.detachPolicy.errorDetails.header":"Errors detaching policy from entities.","policy.details.detachPolicy.errorDetails.template":"Policy not detached from {name}.","policy.details.deletePolicyVersion.errorDetails.header":"Errors deleting policy version.","policy.details.deletePolicyVersion.errorDetails.template":"Policy version {name} not deleted.\\n","policy.details.removeBoundary.errorDetails.header":"Errors removing policy boundary for entities.","policy.details.removeBoundary.errorDetails.template":"Boundary policy not removed for {name}.","policy.details.changeBoundary.errorDetails.header":"Permissions boundary not changed.","policy.details.changeBoundary.errorDetails.template":"Permissions boundary not changed for {name}.","newexperience.policies.list":"Policies list","newexperience.roles.list":"Roles list","newexperience.users.list":"Users list","region.global":"Global Endpoint","role.creation.awsAccount.externalID.description":'You can increase the security of your role by requiring an optional external identifier, which prevents "confused deputy" attacks. This is recommended if you do not own or have administrative access to the account that can assume this role. The external ID can include any characters that you choose. To assume this role, users must be in the trusted account and provide this exact external ID.',"role.creation.awsAccount.externalID.warning":"Important: The console does not support using an external ID with the Switch Role feature. If you select this option, entities in the trusted account must use the API, CLI, or a custom federation proxy to make cross-account iam:AssumeRole calls.","role.creation.attachPolicies.error.detail.header":"Errors attaching policies to the role","role.creation.attachPolicies.error.detail.template":"Policy {name} not attached.\\n","role.creation.permission.tableHeader":"Permissions policies","role.creation.permission.description":"Choose one or more policies to attach to your new role.","role.creation.permission.description.serviceRole":"The type of role that you selected requires the following policy.","role.creation.permission.description.slr":"The service-linked role that you selected requires the following policy.","role.creation.permission.boundary.tableHeader":"Permissions policies","role.creation.permission.boundary.description":"Select policy to set the permissions boundary.","role.details.removePolicySuccess":"Policy removed.","role.details.removePolicyError":"Policy not removed.","role.details.removePolicyLoading":"Removing policy from group.","role.details.removePoliciesSuccess":"Policies removed.","role.details.removePoliciesError":"Policies not removed.","role.details.removePoliciesLoading":"Removing policies from group.","role.details.removeSinglePolicies":"Remove {policy}?","role.details.removeMultiPolicies":"Remove {number} policies?","role.details.removeInlinePolicies":"Remove {number} inline policies?","role.details.removeMultiInlinePolicies":"Remove {number} inline policies?","role.details.inlinePoliciesPlaceholder":"{number} inline policies","role.details.removeSinglePolicyMsg":"All the users in this role will lose the permissions defined in this policy.","role.details.removeMultiPoliciesMsg":"All the users in this role will lose the permissions defined in these policies.","role.details.removeSingleInlinePolicyMsg":"Remove {policy} permanently? This role will lose all the permissions defined in this inline policy and this policy will be deleted.\\n\\nThis action cannot be undone.","role.details.removeMultiInlinePoliciesMsg":"Remove these inline policies permanently? This role will l